{'action': 'opened', 'issue': {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/google/android-fhir/issues/1317', 'repository_url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/google/android-fhir', 'labels_url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/google/android-fhir/issues/1317/labels{/name}', 'comments_url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/google/android-fhir/issues/1317/comments', 'events_url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/google/android-fhir/issues/1317/events', 'html_url': 'https://github.com/google/android-fhir/issues/1317', 'id': 1211286669, 'node_id': 'I_kwDODsfWoc5IMsSN', 'number': 1317, 'title': 'provide testing APIs', 'user': {'login': 'yigit', 'id': 89202, 'node_id': 'MDQ6VXNlcjg5MjAy', 'avatar_url': 'https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/89202?v=4', 'gravatar_id': '', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/users/yigit', 'html_url': 'https://github.com/yigit', 'followers_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/yigit/followers', 'following_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/yigit/following{/other_user}', 'gists_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/yigit/gists{/gist_id}', 'starred_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/yigit/starred{/owner}{/repo}', 'subscriptions_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/yigit/subscriptions', 'organizations_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/yigit/orgs', 'repos_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/yigit/repos', 'events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/yigit/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/yigit/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'labels': [], 'state': 'open', 'locked': False, 'assignee': None, 'assignees': [], 'milestone': None, 'comments': 0, 'created_at': '2022-04-21T16:40:54Z', 'updated_at': '2022-04-21T16:40:54Z', 'closed_at': None, 'author_association': 'COLLABORATOR', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': '`FhirEngineProvider` is currently a singleton, which is not great for tests as it leaks the engine (and the database) between tests (also to the disk so even between test runs).

This bug is to track what to do to better isolate our tests:
* `FhirEngineProvider`'s init method (or the config object) should have a "TestMode" similar to the database:
https://github.com/google/android-fhir/blob/9cffffc28532c77461db3615ca1f57f5c87f6d77/engine/src/main/java/com/google/android/fhir/FhirServices.kt#L44
In test mode, FhirEngineProvider should create the FhirService in memory mode.

* `FhirEngineProvider` should have a `cleanup` method to clear the state (`fhirEngineConfiguration` and `fhirServices`). We will need to change these to `nullable` instead of `lateinit`. Calling `cleanup` outside test mode should should throw an exception.

* We should create a `@TestRule / TestWatcher` that we can add into test classes which will take care of init-deinit for FhirEngineProvider. (call init with test flag BeforeTest and call cleanup in AfterTest).

*Nice To Have*: We could have some initialization code in the test application class that will set some `alwaysRequireTestMode` flag in `FhirEngineProvider` that will make it throw if its configuration is not set for testing. That would allow us to catch cases where someone forgot to apply the rule.

---

As a second step, we should also consider providing an artifact for our clients to write integration tests using the real `FhirEngineProvider`. That API would depend on what we need to provide. WorkManager's testing API might be a good example to follow:
https://developer.android.com/topic/libraries/architecture/workmanager/how-to/integration-testing

cc: [ktarasenko](https://github.com/ktarasenko)

2. Wait before making the leak bigger, this lets the VM react to the GC signal and possibly lets the scheduler dedicate time to GC.

* Pick device version from supported versions

This PR is a quick fix to pick a proper device/version pair.

Previously, we picked default device and default version but it does not
guarantee that the default device supports the default version.

This PR changes that logic to pick the max version from the default
device.
This is a band-aid, we should rewrite this section to pick a device
based on the targetSdk of the APK.

guarantee that the default device supports the default version.

This PR changes that logic to pick the max version from the default
device.

To reproduce, you can run the `XProcessingStepTest.kspProcessingEnvCaching` in AndroidX on a mac machine (checkout repo, `cd room && ./gradlew studio` to open the project).

From my debugging, it seems to be failing on this line:

https://github.com/google/ksp/blob/main/compiler-plugin/src/main/kotlin/com/google/devtools/ksp/KotlinSymbolProcessingExtension.kt#L164

```
newFiles = ksFiles.filter {
                    when (it) {
                        is KSFileImpl -> it.file
                        is KSFileJavaImpl -> it.psi
                        else -> null
                    }?.virtualFile?.let { virtualFile ->
                        virtualFile.canonicalPath ?: virtualFile.path
                    } in newFileNames
                }
```

The path in `newFileNames` is 

```
/private/var/folders/t8/5nj0qf254j99114y1y5v086w007_hl/T/junit853351931968675205/ksp/generatedJava/foo/bar/Main_Impl.java
```

Whereas, the VirtualFile's `myIoFile` field is: `/var/folders/t8/5nj0qf254j99114y1y5v086w007_hl/T/junit853351931968675205/ksp/generatedJava/foo/bar/Main_Impl.java`

(notice the lack of `/private`. In my system, `/var`  is a symlink to `/private/var`

```
ls  -lah /var
lrwxr-xr-x@ 1 root  wheel    11B Feb 25 23:05 /var -> private/var
```
Unfortunately, I cannot debug what `canonicalPath` returns for that file but if I'm finding the source correctly, it seems to simply return the path:

https://upsource.jetbrains.com/idea-ce/file/idea-ce-6a856f22b82f6478cd6fbdc0f281c28d5c75b712/platform/core-api/src/com/intellij/openapi/vfs/VirtualFile.java?nav=11254:11270:focused&line=478&preview=false

+# This workflow creates a new PR with the updated build ids for Playground prebuilts.
+# To run it, navigate to https://github.com/androidx/androidx/actions/workflows/update_prebuilts.yml
+# and click "Run workflow"
+name: Update Prebuilts
+on:
+  workflow_dispatch:
+    inputs:
+      target-branch:
+        description: 'The target branch for the PR'
+        required: false
+        default: 'androidx-main'
+        type: string
+      comment:
+        description: 'Any comment you would like to add to the PR body'
+        required: false
+        default: ''
+        type: string
+jobs:
+  update-prebuilts:
+    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
+    steps:
+      - name: "Checkout androidx repo"
+        uses: actions/checkout@v2
+      - name: "Set environment variables"
+        shell: bash
+        run: development/update_playground.sh
+      - name: "Check if anything changed"
+        shell: bash
+        id: "check-for-changes"
+        run: |
+          set -x
+          git status
+          HAS_CHANGES=`git status --porcelain|grep playground\.properties|wc -l`

+      - name: "Create a PR"
+        shell: bash

+          git config user.email "androidx-github-bot@google.com"
+          git config user.name "AndroidX Github Bot"
+          git checkout -b $BRANCH_NAME

+# This workflow creates a new PR with the updated build ids for Playground prebuilts.
+# To run it, navigate to https://github.com/androidx/androidx/actions/workflows/update_prebuilts.yml
+# and click "Run workflow"
+name: Update Prebuilts
+on:
+  workflow_dispatch:
+    inputs:
+      target-branch:
+        description: 'The target branch for the PR'
+        required: false
+        default: 'androidx-main'
+        type: string
+      comment:
+        description: 'Any comment you would like to add to the PR body'
+        required: false
+        default: ''
+        type: string
+jobs:
+  update-prebuilts:
+    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
+    steps:
+      - name: "Checkout androidx repo"
+        uses: actions/checkout@v2
+      - name: "Set environment variables"
+        shell: bash
+        run: development/update_playground.sh
+      - name: "Check if anything changed"
+        shell: bash
+        id: "check-for-changes"
+        run: |
+          set -x
+          git status
+          HAS_CHANGES=`git status --porcelain|grep playground\.properties|wc -l`
+          echo "::set-output name=has_changes::$HAS_CHANGES"
+      - name: "Create a PR"
+        shell: bash
+        id: "create-pr"
+        if: ${{ steps.check-for-changes.outputs.has_changes >= 1 }}
+        run: |
+          set -x
+          BRANCH_NAME="ci-workflow-bot/update-prebuilts-$(date "+%Y-%m-%d-%H-%M")/${{ github.run_id }}-${{ github.run_number }}"
+          git config user.email "androidx-github-bot@google.com"
+          git config user.name "AndroidX Github Bot"
+          git checkout -b $BRANCH_NAME
+          git add playground-common/playground.properties
+          git commit -m "Update Prebuilts" # PR body overrides this commit message', 'path': '.github/workflows/update_prebuilts.yml', 'position': 46, 'original_position': 46, 'commit_id': +# This workflow creates a new PR with the updated build ids for Playground prebuilts.
+# To run it, navigate to https://github.com/androidx/androidx/actions/workflows/update_prebuilts.yml
+# and click "Run workflow"
+name: Update Prebuilts
+on:
+  workflow_dispatch:
+    inputs:
+      target-branch:
+        description: 'The target branch for the PR'
+        required: false
+        default: 'androidx-main'
+        type: string
+      comment:
+        description: 'Any comment you would like to add to the PR body'
+        required: false
+        default: ''
+        type: string

+        uses: actions/checkout@v2
+      - name: "Set environment variables"
+        shell: bash
+        run: development/update_playground.sh
+      - name: "Check if anything changed"
+        shell: bash
+        id: "check-for-changes"
+        run: |

For input:
```
typealias MyList = MyList<Int>
val x: MyList = TODO()
```

Querying the typeArguments of `x` would return `[Int]` while also returning its declaration as `MyList`.
This makes it looks like `MyList<Int><Int>`.
To fix it, I updated `KSType.arguments` to use the abbreviation type instead of the KotlinType.
Also, updated the test to add more cases and make it print the arguments for each type. I refactored the
test a bit to print types of properties instead of all found types to make the output more readable (happy to revert that part).


Fixes: 881

'closed_at': None, 'author_association': 'NONE', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': 'With room being KSP dependent, if I have this code, 

```
pacakge com.mypackage

@Entity(tableName = "my_data_table")
data class MyData(
}
```

And in other file in the same package, But different fille

```
pacakge com.mypackage

import com.mypackage.DataProvider

data class Identifier<T> private constructor(private val uuid: UUID) {
}

...

typealias DataProviderIdentifier = Identifier<MyData>

```

This compiration with ksp with room gives me 

`
[ksp] java.lang.IllegalStateException: Unexpected type name for KSType: com.mypackage.Identifier<com.mypackage.DataProvider>

`

This makes me think that alias processing happenes before ksp is processing room annotation.

I changed the test a little bit to print type arguments in the signature as well and also group by final signature for equality checks.

Good news, equality checks seems to be working, bad news; it is printing the extra type arguments.
Line 7-11 from the output:

```
ListOfInt<Int> = List<Int>
ListOfInt<Int> = List<Int>
ListOfInt_B<Int> = ListOfInt<Int> = List<Int>
ListOfInt_B<Int> = ListOfInt<Int> = List<Int>
ListOfInt_C<Int> = ListOfInt_B<Int> = ListOfInt<Int> = List<Int>
```

Where `ListOfInt<Int> = List<Int>` should've been `ListOfInt = List<Int>` because it is declared as:

```
pacakge com.mypackage

@Entity(tableName = "my_data_table")
data class MyData(
}
```

And in other file in the same package, But different fille

```
pacakge com.mypackage

import com.mypackage.DataProvider

data class Identifier<T> private constructor(private val uuid: UUID) {
}

...

typealias DataProviderIdentifier = Identifier<MyData>

Currently Room uses "ABORT" resolution strategy as a default. It means that for `@Insert` and `@Update` annotated methods, Room compiler generates SQL code containing on conflict statements. This prevents INSERT/UPDATE triggers from specifying their own resolution strategy. SQLite is already using "ABORT" strategy as a default when no on conflict statement is present.

This change adds "NONE" conflict resolution strategy and makes it a default. If "NONE" strategy is set, then Room compiler won't generate on conflict statements for @Insert and @Update annotated methods.

## Testing

Test: /gradlew test connectedCheck

## Issues Fixed

```Kotlin

It points to the following top-level property which performs some static initialization within `ReactiveFlow.kt`:
```Kotlin
// ContextInjector service is implemented in `kotlinx-coroutines-reactor` module only.

    ServiceLoader.load(ContextInjector::class.java, ContextInjector::class.java.classLoader).toList()

All PRs must be linked to an issue (except for extremely trivial and straightforward changes).**

Fixes #1199 

**Description**
1. DataSource interface is changed to support apis for just  Bundle based upload and download of the resources.
2. DataSource is implemented by Engine and is now longer exposed to the outer application.
3. Downloader interface is introduced similar to the Uploader interface to abstract away the details from FhirSynchronizer.

**Alternative(s) considered**
Have you considered any alternatives? And if so, why have you chosen the approach in this PR?

trivial and straightforward changes).**

Fixes #1199 

**Description**
1. DataSource interface is changed to support apis for just  Bundle based upload and download of the resources.
2. DataSource is implemented by Engine and is now longer exposed to the outer application.
3. Downloader interface is introduced similar to the Uploader interface to abstract away the details from FhirSynchronizer.

trivial and straightforward changes).**

Fixes #1199 

**Description**
1. DataSource interface is changed to support apis for just  Bundle based upload and download of the resources.
2. DataSource is implemented by Engine and is now longer exposed to the outer application.
3. Downloader interface is introduced similar to the Uploader interface to abstract away the details from FhirSynchronizer.

**Alternative(s) considered**
Have you considered any alternatives? And if so, why have you chosen the approach in this PR?

**Type**
Choose one: Feature

Fixes #1199 

**Description**
1. DataSource interface is changed to support apis for just  Bundle based upload and download of the resources.
2. DataSource is implemented by Engine and is now longer exposed to the outer application.
3. Downloader interface is introduced similar to the Uploader interface to abstract away the details from FhirSynchronizer.

input:

```
interface NestedDataClassSubject {
    data class NestedDataClass(
      val field: String,
     )
  }
```

Calling `NestedDataClass.isOpen` returns `true` instead of `false`.

Looks like it is coming from [this line](https://github.com/google/ksp/blob/main/api/src/main/kotlin/com/google/devtools/ksp/utils.kt#L218) but it is very old code so I couldn't figure out why we check for the parent declaration's `classKind`.

I've not tested but reading the code, this probably affects any other code. 

Related room issue: https://issuetracker.google.com/issues/221280927
